    id: "ethics-amedex-0071",
    topic: "Ethics & Professionalism",
    subtopic: "Witnessing a Will and Legal Formalities",
    stem: `You are a general practitioner in a general clinic. Albert and Mandy, husband and wife, are your regular patients. Albert has diabetes and recently survived a myocardial infarction. Mandy has come to you today and shows you a will that she says is signed by Albert. She says that Albert has made changes to his previous will and now this new will is signed by him. She asks you to sign the will as a witness. What should be your response to her request?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Sign the will.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Refuse to sign the will.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Call Albert and ask if he confirms the will.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Seek legal advice from your medical indemnity.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Ask you clinic manager if you can sign the will.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Under succession law, a will must be signed in front of at least two people as witnesses. The purpose of witnesses is to provide a safeguard for the prevention of fraud and forgery. Any person above the age of 18 years with mental capacity and credibility to give evidence in a court of law can witness a will, with exceptions for those unable to see the signing and those who will inherit under the will. The most appropriate response is to refuse to sign the will because you have not witnessed Albert's signing the will in person. You cannot witness something you have not personally witnessed. Calling Albert to ask if he confirms the will (option C) is incorrect because you still have not seen him in person signing the will. Signing the will (option A) is ethically and professionally wrong. Seeking legal advice from your medical indemnity (option D) or asking your clinic manager (option E) is unnecessary in this clear-cut case based on common sense and ethical principles.`,
    reference: "amc",
    difficulty: "medium",
