    id: "psych-amedex-0016",
    topic: "Psychiatry",
    subtopic: "Bipolar disorder depression management",
    stem: `A 50-year-old man with a past medical history of bipolar disorder with psychotic features presents to you, complaining of decreased mood and appetite for the past two weeks. On examination, you notice that he does not talk much and only answers your questions briefly. He seems to have decreased concentration and avoid eye contact. He, however, denies hallucinations and paranoid ideation. He is currently on olanzapine, which he has been taking for the past two years. Which of the following is the most appropriate initial management of this patient?`,
