    correctAnswer: "E",
    explanation: `Many mood stabilisers (olanzapine here) have a bimodal effect. They can be used for the treatment of both depression and mania. If a patient who has successfully been stable on a prophylactic dose of a particular mood stabiliser develops acute depression, two approaches can be considered with about the same efficacy: Adding an antidepressant to the prophylactic mood stabiliser: the choices of the drug would be the same as for major depression. SSRIs are first-line options. Increasing the dose of prophylactic mood stabiliser. Either the addition of escitalopram or increasing the dose of olanzapine can be effectively used for this patient. NOTE - Cessation or dose reduction of a mood stabiliser can result in a relapse of mania and is not appropriate.`,
