    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `Angry and agitated patients usually present a challenge to healthcare providers. The best approach is to calm down the patient in tactful, professional manners, ideally without using sedatives; however, when the patient is feared to pose harm to themselves or medical staff, hospital security must be called, and the patient must be sedated. Since this patient is at high risk for violence due to his psychiatric condition and history of violence, calling the hospital security and sedating him would be the next best step in management. The zero-tolerance policy to violence is adopted in all Australian emergency departments. This policy mandates sedation on the slightest concern of harm from the patients either to themselves or the staff. The medications of choice for this purpose include haloperidol (preferred) and midazolam. Midazolam carries the risk of respiratory depression and hypotension and should be used with great caution. Benzodiazepines are the first-line when agitation is likely to have been caused by alcohol intoxication or withdrawal. Patients needing medical attention should be treated, not handed to the Police or escorted out.`,
