    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Depression is common among patients with ESRD and on dialysis. It is a major cause of treatment withdrawal in such patients. However, sudden decline associated with findings of fever and abdominal tenderness is against depression as the cause of treatment refusal in this patient. This patient's fever and abdominal tenderness point towards infection. Infections may cause delirium, especially in aging people. For delirium to be the underlying cause of this presentation, disorientation should be present during the examination. Depressed mood (option B) is an unlikely finding in a patient who has been coping well so far, but all of a sudden refuses treatment. Blunted affect (option C), delusions (option D) and hypervigilance (option E) would have been expected in psychotic mental disorders. Such disorders usually have a more insidious onset, making them less likely explanations in this scenario.`,
