    id: "psych-amedex-0041",
    topic: "Psychiatry",
    subtopic: "Bipolar disorder management in pregnancy",
    stem: `A 26-year-old woman with a background history of difficult-to-treat bipolar disorder is planning to conceive. She has been stable on lithium and quetiapine for the last six months. Which one of the following would be the next best step in management?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Explain the pros and cons of lithium use during pregnancy and continue the medication.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Switch to sodium valproate.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Switch to lamotrigine.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Start the patient on antipsychotics.` },
      { label: "E", text: `Taper and stop lithium before conception.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Although lithium use during the first trimester of pregnancy has been reported to be associated with fetal cardiovascular anomalies (e.g. Epstein's anomaly) and midfacial and other defects, benefits to the mother substantially outweigh the risks of fetal anomaly. For pregnant women stable on lithium, one approach can be careful withdrawal of lithium (or other mood stabilisers) to avoid potential risks to the developing fetus. Some authorities discourage this method because of the risk of relapse. In this patient, however, the history of difficult-to-treat bipolar disorder that has just recently responded to lithium after failed trials of other mood stabilisers makes such an approach less favourable. She should be maintained on lithium to avoid relapse. In such situations, the woman should be fully informed of the risks and decision-making left to the patient. If the woman decides to conceive, lithium should be continued throughout the pregnancy, and ultrasound and echocardiogram should be performed at 16-20 weeks gestation to exclude fetal anomalies, especially cardiac anomalies. Option B: Sodium valproate is teratogenic and contraindicated in pregnancy. Switching to sodium valproate can be associated with a high risk of relapse as well as more harm to the fetus. Option C: Lamotrigine is an option for the prevention of bipolar depression. It is not effective in prevention or treatment of manic episodes. Option D: According to a recent meta-analysis, antipsychotics, especially risperidone, olanzapine, and haloperidol, are superior to other mood stabilisers such as lithium, sodium valproate, and carbamazepine for the treatment of manic episodes and are recommended as first-line options for this purpose. Still, if the risk of relapse is high, lithium should be used concomitantly for a maintained therapeutic response. While this patient is stable on lithium, switching to withdrawal of lithium and commencement of antipsychotics is likely to result in a relapse. Option E: As mentioned earlier, stopping medications in a stable patient might be considered, but for this patient, such action can result in relapse of the disease.`,
