    correctAnswer: "B",
    explanation: `The clinical history of this patient is consistent with acute mania, probably due to bipolar I disorder. Bipolar I disorder is a mood disturbance characterised by manic symptoms of at least one-week duration. The symptoms should be significant enough to cause considerable impairment or distress in functioning. Characteristic features of bipolar disorder include: Persistent abnormally elevated mood lasting for at least one week; Increased self-esteem and grandiosity; Distractibility; Excessive involvement in activities; More talkative than usual – pressured speech is often noticed on examination; Psychomotor agitation; Flights of ideas; Increased sexual activity; Increase in goal-directed activities. Of the given options, lithium is the drug of choice for both acute treatment and maintenance therapy. Antipsychotics such as olanzapine, quetiapine (option E), risperidone, and aripiprazole can be used in combination with lithium or alone for acute mania. Sodium valproate (option A), in combination with atypical antipsychotics, is an alternative in specific patients. NOTE - it is recommended that patients with acute mania in a bipolar disorder setting should be started on a short course of antipsychotics and a 6- to 12-month course of mood stabiliser concurrently. Haloperidol (option D) is used for patients with acute manic features who need sedation. If the patient is not cooperative and acutely agitated, intramuscular haloperidol would be the best initial management. Carbamazepine (option C) and some other anticonvulsants have been used as mood stabilisers, but evidence shows it is less effective than lithium or atypical antipsychotics in the management of acute mania in bipolar disorder.`,
