    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `SSRIs such as sertraline, fluoxetine, paroxetine, fluvoxamine, citalopram, etc., are well-known to be associated with sexual dysfunction as one of their most prominent adverse effects that could lead to noncompliance. The reported sexual adverse outcomes of SSRIs include decreased libido, delayed ejaculation (this effect has been used for treatment of premature ejaculation), erectile dysfunction, and painful ejaculation. Strategies have been proposed for dealing with the sexual adverse effects of SSRIs, including drug holidays, dose reduction, switching to another antidepressant with minimal or no impact on sexual functioning such as bupropion, mirtazapine, or nefazodone, and use of phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitors such as sildenafil or tadalafil, and cognitive behavioural therapy. Of these options, however, using a phosphodiesterase type 5 inhibitor such as sildenafil before intercourse has become the standard of care. (Option A) Switching to other SSRIs, such as fluoxetine, fluvoxamine, paroxetine, etc, is unlikely to resolve the problem because these drugs are associated with sexual dysfunction as well. (Option B) Cessation of sertraline may result in a relapse of the recently controlled depression. (Option D) Decreasing the current dose of sertraline in a patient who has just responded to the incremental dose increase due to uncontrolled depressive symptoms is very likely to result in relapse; therefore, it is not an appropriate option. (Option E) Clomipramine is a tricyclic antidepressant used for the treatment of premature ejaculation. Addition of clomipramine will deteriorate delayed ejaculation.`,
