    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `The scenario is consistent with a diagnosis of an acute psychotic episode in the early postpartum period. A few explanations should be considered and investigated. The most important ones include: substance-induced psychotic disorder (substance intoxication/withdrawal), brief psychotic disorder, and postpartum psychosis. Considering the time of the presentation (shortly after delivery) and another physical finding, drug intoxication as a likely cause should be excluded first. For this purpose, a urine drug screen test is the most appropriate measure. A rare yet important diagnosis to consider is postpartum psychosis. The condition most commonly presents within two weeks of childbirth. Hallucinations and delusions are usually present, often with thought disorganisation and/or bizarre behaviour. Although one should have postpartum psychosis as one possible diagnosis, more prevalent aetiologies for an acute psychotic episode should be considered and excluded first, especially with the very early onset of symptoms, which seems somewhat unusual (but not impossible) for postpartum psychosis. Options A, B, and E: At 37.5°C, it is very unlikely that an infectious process caused this presentation; hence, blood culture, FBC, and UA are not appropriate steps, at least not as the most important initial approach. Option D: CT scan of the head would have been indicated as a part of initial management if there was a pointer towards an intracranial pathology.`,
