    explanation: `The scenario fulfils the classic definition of hypomania. This woman can have her first hypomanic episode of bipolar disorder (type II) disorder. A hypomanic episode is characterised by a distinct period of persistently elevated, expansive, or irritable mood, lasting at least four days and present for most of the day nearly every day. This hypomanic mood is different from the person's usual mood. Features seen in hypomania include inflated self-esteem and grandiosity, decreased need for sleep, more talkativeness than usual and pressured speech, distractibility, increased goal-directed activities, increased sexual drive, and excessive involvement in pleasurable activities that have a high potential for painful consequences. For patients with hypomania and mild to moderate manic episodes, monotherapy with risperidone or olanzapine is currently the first-line recommendation. Unlike mania, which is an emergency, hypomania does not always require pharmacotherapy. But in general, medical treatment of a manic episode starts with the immediate use of an antipsychotic for the short term and the concurrent commencement of a mood stabilizer for 6-12 months. Prophylaxis may be required afterwards. Lithium and carbamazepine are not first-line for acute mania. Lamotrigine is an anticonvulsant successfully used for the prevention of depression episodes in patients with bipolar disorder. Its effect in the treatment or prophylaxis of mania or hypomania has not proved satisfactory. Benzodiazepines are considered in manic patients who cannot tolerate any of the other mood stabilisers, or in those who are agitated. With the wide range of mood stabilisers available, monotherapy with benzodiazepines is rarely indicated; however, lorazepam and clonazepam are used in the short term and in combination with mood stabilisers for rapid resolution of mania. Diazepam is not used for such purposes.`,
