    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD) is characterised by recurrent obsessions or compulsions that the individual recognises as unreasonable. Obsessions are anxiety-provoking, intrusive thoughts commonly concerning contamination, doubt, guilt, aggression and sex. Compulsions are peculiar behaviours that reduce anxiety, such as hand washing, organising, checking, counting, etc. Abnormalities of serotonin metabolism are most implicated as the underlying cause of OCD. OCD is best treated with a specific form of behaviour therapy—exposure and preventive response and/or selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs)—as the first-line medications. All SSRIs have about the same efficacy. The TCA clomipramine has also been used as a treatment option and was the medication of choice before SSRIs took over. Serotonin-norepinephrine reuptake inhibitors (SNRIs), such as venlafaxine, can be used as an alternative, but SSRIs remain the preferred option. Benzodiazepines may be considered for anxiety relief in the short term, but they are not effective in the treatment of OCD. Although alcohol consumption is associated with decreased compulsive behaviour in the short term, its use is not recommended for the treatment of OCD due to the high risk of dependence and abuse. Antipsychotics have been shown to add to the benefits of SSRIs or clomipramine, but these medications are not used for single therapy in OCD.`,
