    explanation: `The presence of a gap in one's memory, during which the person has often travelled and done things he cannot recall, makes dissociative fugue the most likely diagnosis. The diagnosis is endorsed by the presence of an emotional stressor (being fired from work). Automatism (option A) refers to brief unconscious behaviours that typically last for several seconds to minutes or sometimes longer. Major depression (option B) has a completely different presentation with low mood, lack of energy, poor concentration, altered appetite/sleep, etc. for at least two weeks. The key finding in depersonalisation (option C) is an out-of-body experience, but that is not the case here. Derealisation (option D) is associated with a distorted perception of the environment characterised by jamais vu, déjà vu, and other peculiar feelings about the physical environment. A psychological stressor is the main risk factor for most dissociative disorders. For dissociative disorder, prolonged childhood sexual abuse has been hypothesised to be the most significant risk factor.`,
