    explanation: `The clinical scenario is most consistent with dementia. Dementia is a progressive decline in general cognitive function, with normal consciousness and attention. There is impairment of memory, abstract thinking, judgment, verbal fluency and the ability to perform complex tasks. It is associated with behavioural and psychological changes and social and physical functioning impairment. Behavioural and psychological symptoms of dementia include psychosis, depression, agitation, aggression and social disgrace. Of the given options, frontotemporal dementia (Pick disease) is most consistent with the clinical scenario. Frontotemporal dementia is characterised by focal degeneration of the frontal and/or temporal lobes. The typical age of onset is in the late 50s or early 60s, and the primary clinical manifestations are changes in personality and social behaviour or language, progressing over time to more global dementia. Other features include impaired initiation and planning, disinhibited behaviour and social disgrace, and mild abnormalities in cognitive testing. Apathy and memory deficits develop later in the course of the disease. A subset of patients may also exhibit extrapyramidal or motor neuron involvement symptoms at some point in the disease process. Option A: Delusional misidentification syndromes are rare psychopathologic phenomena that may occur within the context of schizophrenia or affective or organic illnesses. They include Capgras syndrome, Fregoli syndrome, intermetamorphosis syndrome, syndrome of subjective doubles, mirrored self, delusional companions, and clonal pluralisation of the self. Misidentification syndromes show a great degree of overlap and do not represent distinctive syndromes. There is no clue in the scenario to point towards delusional syndromes. Option B: Alzheimer's disease is the most common cause of irreversible dementia. It is characterised by forgetfulness early in the course of the disease, and behavioural changes develop late in the course. Anne's presenting symptoms are behavioural changes that are unlikely to develop early in Alzheimer's disease. Option C: Psychosis typically presents with hallucinations and delusions, the absence of which in the scenario makes this diagnosis unlikely. Option E: Patients with paranoid type schizophrenia present with a preoccupation with one or more delusions and hallucinations, usually involving grandeur or persecution.`,
