    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `The patient's speech demonstrates circumstantiality. The speech starts with an unrelated topic (whales) but eventually returns to the starting point (answering the question about family history of mental illness with 'we are all sane and sound'). Circumstantiality occurs when the patient drifts from one topic to another but eventually reaches the destination. Unlike derailment (option D), where the patient never returns to the original topic, or tangentiality (option E), where there is only a hint linking consecutive topics, circumstantiality has many detours but reaches the goal. Flight of ideas (option A) is characterised by over-productive speech rapidly shifting from one topic to another with a subjective feeling of racing thoughts, and the topic is organised but over-productive and excessively detailed. Word salad (option B) involves throwing words together without sensible or intelligible meaning.`,
