    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Borderline personality disorder (BPD) is the best explanation for this scenario. The excessive fear of being abandoned is one of the key features of BPD. These abandonment fears are related to intolerance of being alone and the need to have other people around. Frantic efforts are made to avoid imagined abandonment, including impulsive actions such as self-mutilating or suicidal behaviour. To this woman, discharge conveys abandonment, and she is trying to prevent it. Option A (Narcissistic personality disorder) is characterised by a sense of self-importance, grandiosity, and preoccupation with fantasies of success. Option B (Histrionic personality disorder) is characterised by colorful, exaggerated behaviour and shallow expression of emotions. Option D (Factitious disorder) involves conscious production of signs and symptoms with the main objective of assuming the sick role, with motivation at a subconscious level. Option E (Malingering) is also conscious production of signs and symptoms but with an apparent gain such as money or avoidance of work. Note: Dependent personality disorder (DPD) can also present similarly, with individuals preoccupied with the need to be taken care of, clinging behaviour, and unrealistically worried about abandonment. Studies suggest over 50% of patients with BPD also meet criteria for DPD.`,
