    correctAnswer: "A",
    explanation: `Lewy body dementia is the most consistent diagnosis based on the clinical features presented. Key diagnostic features include: recent onset forgetfulness and peculiar behaviour, and importantly, visual hallucinations (seeing people that do not exist). These features suggest Lewy body dementia as the most consistent diagnosis among the options. Lewy body dementia is a progressive, degenerative dementia of unknown aetiology, presenting with dementia, motor signs, episodes of reduced cognition and visual hallucinations. Unlike Parkinson's disease, in Lewy body dementia, cognitive impairment and dementia precede extrapyramidal manifestations. Lewy body dementia presents with: dementia and fluctuations in cognitive function with varying levels of alertness and attention during the day; episodes of long staring and disorganised speech; well-formed, detailed visual hallucinations (or less commonly, auditory); Parkinsonian motor features; early extrapyramidal features; anterograde memory loss; and visuospatial impairment. Option B (Alzheimer's disease): Although forgetfulness is a prominent early feature, spontaneous motor Parkinsonism, hallucinations, and peculiar behaviour develop late in the course, often in a matter of years. Option C (Delusional disorder): There is no false belief in the scenario—the imagined people entering his house are visual hallucinations, not delusions. Option D (Schizophrenia): Although hallucinations are characteristic, patients with schizophrenia usually have auditory rather than visual hallucinations. Moreover, the age of the patient is unusual for the development of schizophrenia. Option E (Frontotemporal dementia): Even though early behavioural changes are a feature, the presence of visual hallucinations makes Lewy body dementia the more likely diagnosis. Furthermore, forgetfulness is not a prominent feature early in frontotemporal dementia.`,
