    correctAnswer: "C",
    explanation: `Serum gonadotropins (FSH and LH) are not diagnostically valuable in anorexia nervosa. The investigations indicated for all patients presenting with anorexia nervosa include: serum electrolytes (option D), blood urea nitrogen, serum creatinine, serum glucose, serum calcium, phosphorous, and magnesium; thiamine; serum albumin; liver function tests (option A) including aspartate aminotransferase, alanine aminotransferase, and alkaline phosphatase; Internationalized Normalized Ratio (INR); complete blood count (CBC) including differential; erythrocyte sedimentation rate; thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH); electrocardiogram (ECG) (option B); and urinalysis for specific gravity. A dual-energy absorptiometry (DXA) scan (option E) is also indicated for all patients with anorexia nervosa of longer than six months duration to assess for osteopenia or osteoporosis. For this patient with a 2-year history, a DXA scan should be performed. FSH and LH are not diagnostically valuable where the diagnosis of anorexia nervosa is evident based on the presence of emaciation in conjunction with self-induced starvation and intense fear of weight gain. In such cases, amenorrhea is the result of underlying malnutrition and estrogen deficiency (hypopituitary hypogonadism). Measurement of FSH/LH is only indicated if the diagnosis of anorexia nervosa cannot be clinched through physical exams and history and other causes of amenorrhea, such as ovarian failure, have been considered.`,
