    explanation: `The scenario is a typical presentation of generalised anxiety disorder (GAD). GAD is characterised by experiencing excessive anxiety and worry, often about health, family, financial issues, or work. This worrying goes on every day, possibly all day long. It negatively interferes with social activities and is associated with impaired work, school, or family function. GAD is diagnosed in adults when they experience at least 3 of the following symptoms on more days for at least six months: restlessness or feeling keyed up or on edge, being easily fatigued, difficulty concentrating or mind going blank, irritability, muscle tension, and sleep disturbance. To make the diagnosis in children, only one symptom is required. Major depression is associated with depressed mood, which is not present in this woman. Depression and dysthymic disorder can be seen in patients with GAD. Adjustment disorder requires one provocative event to be present, and there is no recent stressor in the history. OCD is associated with obsessions and impulses with no clue in the history to suggest such a diagnosis.`,
