    explanation: `This young boy has presented with symptoms suggestive of depression after an identifiable stressor (the breakup). He has the criteria for 'adjustment disorder' as the most likely diagnosis. The DSM-5 diagnostic criteria for adjustment disorder require emotional or behavioural symptoms develop in response to an identifiable stressor or stressors within three months of the onset of the stressor(s). The most appropriate next step is to establish rapport using active listening and empathy, non-directional supportive psychotherapy, and psycho-education (STEP 1 of the RACGP model). CBT (option B) can be considered in STEP 2 afterwards. Patients with depression in the setting of adjustment disorder usually respond to brief non-pharmacological interventions and do not require anti-depressants such as fluoxetine (option C) and fluvoxamine (option D). Referral to a psychiatrist (option E) is optional for adjustment disorder and should be considered after establishing an appropriate therapeutic relationship with the patient.`,
