    topic: "Psychiatry",
    subtopic: "Obsessive-Compulsive Disorder",
    stem: `Exposure and response prevention is the treatment option for which one of the following conditions?`,
    options: [
      { label: "A", text: `Bipolar disorder.` },
      { label: "B", text: `Depression.` },
      { label: "C", text: `Agoraphobia.` },
      { label: "D", text: `Obsessive – compulsive disorder (OCD).` },
      { label: "E", text: `Schizophrenia.` },
    ],
    correctAnswer: "D",
    explanation: `Exposure and response (or ritual) prevention (ERP) is an essential and specific core element in behaviour therapy for obsessive-compulsive disorder (OCD). OCD is characterised by distressing, intrusive, obsessive thoughts and/or repetitive compulsive physical or mental acts, often in the form of rituals. The mainstays of treatment of OCD include the use of selective serotonin reuptake inhibitors (SSRIs) or the TCA clomipramine, ERP, some forms of cognitive behaviour therapy), education and family interventions, and, in highly refractory cases, neurosurgery. In ERP, the situations the patients perceive as threatening are ranked. Then, the patient is systematically exposed to gradually increasing intensity symptom triggers and is taught to suppress their usual ritualised response. ERP is generally challenging and often quite distressing for the patient, but when effectively done, it promotes unlearning of the strong link that has existed between having an urge and giving in to the urge.`,
